\subsection{Search Modes \& Heuristics}\label{search-modes-heuristics}

\textbf{kNN} --- Standard top-k retrieval using HNSW's
\texttt{searchKnnCloserFirst}. Return order depends on metric: - L2:
lower distance is better (ascending sort) - Cosine / Inner-product:
higher value is better (descending sort after converting distances if
needed)

\textbf{Radius} --- Return all candidates with score \textgreater=
threshold (for cosine) or \textless= threshold (for L2). Implement by
retrieving a large candidate list (\texttt{cfg.max\_elements} or an
upper-bounded \texttt{k}) then filtering.

\textbf{Relative} --- Keep results within
\texttt{alpha\ *\ best\_score}.

\textbf{Adaptive} --- Retrieve a lookahead number of results, apply
\texttt{minN}, then apply a \texttt{gapDelta} heuristic: stop when
consecutive score gap exceeds \texttt{gapDelta} after at least
\texttt{minN} results are kept.

\textbf{Ranking heuristic suggestions:} combine: - absolute threshold
(minScore) - relative threshold (alpha × top) - gap detection (lookahead
+ gapDelta) - cluster-aware cutoff (use top-N and cluster-distance
heuristics)

\begin{center}\rule{0.5\linewidth}{0.5pt}\end{center}

\subsection{💾 FIle Formats /
Persistence}\label{file-formats-persistence}

\begin{longtable}[]{@{}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\linewidth - 4\tabcolsep) * \real{0.1515}}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\linewidth - 4\tabcolsep) * \real{0.2273}}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\linewidth - 4\tabcolsep) * \real{0.6212}}@{}}
\toprule\noalign{}
\begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
Component
\end{minipage} & \begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
Storage File
\end{minipage} & \begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
Notes
\end{minipage} \\
\midrule\noalign{}
\endhead
\bottomrule\noalign{}
\endlastfoot
Sentences & \texttt{sentences.txt} & UTF-8 text, newline-delimited \\
Offsets & \texttt{offsets.bin} & Binary, mmap-backed \\
HNSW index & \texttt{index.hix} & Saved periodically or at
flush/destructor \\
\end{longtable}

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \texttt{sentences.txt} --- newline-delimited UTF-8 sentences or
  chunks. Each appended chunk's start/end byte offsets are stored in
  \texttt{OffsetEntry}.
\item
  \texttt{offsets.bin} --- mmap-backed binary file with optional header
  and an array of \texttt{OffsetEntry}. Header may store meta fields:
  format version, dim, metric, normalized flag, element\_count.
\item
  \texttt{index.hix} --- HNSW binary graph saved by
  \texttt{hnsw\_index-\textgreater{}saveIndex()}. Can optionally be
  prefixed by a small header or stored separately as
  \texttt{\textless{}base\textgreater{}.hnsw}.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Metadata header (optional)}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{struct}\NormalTok{ IndexMeta }\OperatorTok{\{}
    \DataTypeTok{uint32\_t}\NormalTok{ version}\OperatorTok{;}
    \DataTypeTok{char}\NormalTok{ metric}\OperatorTok{[}\DecValTok{16}\OperatorTok{];}        \CommentTok{// "L2", "cosine", "ip"}
    \DataTypeTok{bool}\NormalTok{ normalized}\OperatorTok{;}        \CommentTok{// were embeddings normalized on insert?}
    \DataTypeTok{uint32\_t}\NormalTok{ dim}\OperatorTok{;}
    \DataTypeTok{uint64\_t}\NormalTok{ element\_count}\OperatorTok{;}
\OperatorTok{\};}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

If you prefix the HNSW file with \texttt{IndexMeta}, ensure the HNSW
loader is able to seek after the header (or use stream-based load API).

\begin{center}\rule{0.5\linewidth}{0.5pt}\end{center}

\subsection{Concurrency \& Performance}\label{concurrency-performance}

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{Parallel search:} query shards in parallel, then merge top-k
  results. Use a thread pool or \texttt{std::async} and aggregate.
\item
  \textbf{Parallel merge:} when merging two shards, collect
  \texttt{(text,\ sid)} pairs concurrently, then append to the merged
  index using multiple threads. Guard SBERT inference concurrency to
  limit per-thread GGML memory pressure.
\item
  \textbf{Flush strategy:} keep offsets in mmap and msync single-entry
  updates; batch HNSW saves using \texttt{dirty\_count} and
  \texttt{cfg.flush\_every} threshold to balance durability and
  throughput.
\item
  \textbf{Memory safety on macOS:} call
  \texttt{relax\_macos\_malloc\_zones()} (or set
  \texttt{MallocNanoZone=0}) before loading large ggml or HNSW buffers
  to avoid the ``nano zone abandoned'' message and fragmentation issues.
\item
  Memory-mapped I/O for minimal disk overhead.
\item
  Optional compile-time thread cache.
\end{itemize}

\begin{center}\rule{0.5\linewidth}{0.5pt}\end{center}

\subsection{🧩 Future Extensions}\label{future-extensions}

